$BestModel
$BestModel$model.description
[1] "This is a qualitative description of the best found model by the estimation package. See also the field $key.properties for quantative descriptions. OUOU model. Multiple traits under stabilizing selection, adapting to a deterministic optimum. All traits are adapting independently to the primary optimum. All dependencies between traits are due to the random perturbations. "

$BestModel$parameter.SE
[1] "The function did not calculate any confidence intervals as this takes a long time. You have to do it manually. Here is code to call: ,parametric.bootstrap(estimated.model=your_estimated_model,phyltree=your_phylogenetic_tree,values.to.bootstrap=c(vector of parameter names, e.g.: \"evolutionary.regression\", \"optimal.regression\"),regimes=your_regimes,root.regime=your_root_regime (does not need to be provided),M.error=your_measurement_error,predictors=your_predictors (if you want conditional distributions reported),numboot=desired number of bootstrap replicates,Atype=your_Atype,Syytype=your_Syytype,diagA=your_diagonal_of_A,parameter_signs=your_parameter_signs, and see other technical parameters in manual)where  your_estimated_model_parameters are the estimated parameters \n    (can be found in the slot $BestModel$BestModel$ParamsInModel in the returned object), \n    your_phylogenetic_tree is your phylogeny in ape (phylo) format (passed to the parameter phyltree \n    when calling evol.model.est), your_measurement_error is your measurement error structure \n    (passed to the parameter M.error when calling evol.model.est, may be left NULL), \n    your_predictors are your indicated predictor variables (passed to the parameter predictors when calling \n    evol.model.est, may be left NULL), \n    your_regimes is your regimes vector (passed to the parameter regimes when calling evol.model.est), \n    your_Atype is the class to which the A matrix belongs in the best found model \n    (can be found in the slot $BestModel$model$Atype in the returned object), \n    your_Syytype is the class to which the A matrix belongs in the best found model \n    (can be found in the slot $BestModel$model$Syytype in the returned object) and your_parameter_signs are the signs of parameters\n    you assumed (if you did, read the manual files on this first!). "

$BestModel$BestModel$ParamSummary$RSS$RSS_non_phylogenetic_conditional_on_predictors_comment
[1] "WARNING: the covariance matrix for species 31,32,37,42,43,44,48,64,65,66,67,68,70,71,72,73,74,75,76,77,78,79,80,81,82,83,84,92,93,94,95,96,97 is not symmetric positive definite! Trying to correct with Matrix::nearPD. Non-phylogenetic RSS calculations are highly doubtful!  This is probably the result of the optimizer getting stuck at some extreme value, you are advised to rerun the optimization. A possible explanation is that the search procedure finished in a very bad local maximum of the likelihood surface. One suggested solution is to re-run on a simpler, i.e. fewer free parameters and then use the output as a starting point for the considered here model. A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

$BestModel$BestModel$ParamSummary$confidence.interval$regression.summary$regression.confidence.interval.comment
[1] "These are confidence intervals for parameters estimated by a GLS conditional on the A and diffusion matrix parameters. In the full covariance matrix of the regression estimators the matrix parameters are entered column wise for the deterministic optimum and row wise for the B matrix. Be careful if some of the parameters were set at fixed values in the user's input, i.e. check if the variances correctly correspond to the presented 95% CIs. These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

One suggested solution is to re-run on a simpler, i.e. fewer free parameters and then use the output as a starting point for the considered here model. A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

One suggested solution is to re-run on a simpler, i.e. fewer free parameters and then use the output as a starting point for the considered here model. A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

In the full covariance matrix of the regression estimators the matrix parameters are entered column wise for the deterministic optimum and row wise for the B matrix. These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

One suggested solution is to re-run on a simpler, i.e. fewer free parameters and then use the output as a starting point for the considered here model. A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

$testedModels[[17]]$result$FinalFound$ParamSummary$confidence.interval$regression.summary$regression.confidence.interval.comment
[1] "These are confidence intervals for parameters estimated by a GLS conditional on the A and diffusion matrix parameters. In the full covariance matrix of the regression estimators the matrix parameters are entered column wise for the deterministic optimum and row wise for the B matrix. Be careful if some of the parameters were set at fixed values in the user's input, i.e. check if the variances correctly correspond to the presented 95% CIs. These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

[1] "R2 is negative, consider rerunning estimation or a different model of evolution. A possible explanation is that the search procedure finished in a very bad local maximum of the likelihood surface. One suggested solution is to re-run on a simpler, i.e. fewer free parameters and then use the output as a starting point for the considered here model. A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

A possible explanation is that the search procedure finished in a very bad local maximum of the likelihood surface. One suggested solution is to re-run on a simpler, i.e. fewer free parameters and then use the output as a starting point for the considered here model. A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

[1] "These are confidence intervals for parameters estimated by a GLS conditional on the A and diffusion matrix parameters. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

$testedModels[[58]]$result$FinalFound$ParamSummary$confidence.interval$regression.summary$regression.confidence.interval.comment
[1] "These are confidence intervals for parameters estimated by a GLS conditional on the A and diffusion matrix parameters. In the full covariance matrix of the regression estimators the matrix parameters are entered column wise for the deterministic optimum and row wise for the B matrix. Be careful if some of the parameters were set at fixed values in the user's input, i.e. check if the variances correctly correspond to the presented 95% CIs. These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

$testedModels[[64]]$result$FinalFound$ParamSummary$confidence.interval$regression.summary$regression.confidence.interval.comment
[1] "These are confidence intervals for parameters estimated by a GLS conditional on the A and diffusion matrix parameters. In the full covariance matrix of the regression estimators the matrix parameters are entered column wise for the deterministic optimum and row wise for the B matrix. Be careful if some of the parameters were set at fixed values in the user's input, i.e. check if the variances correctly correspond to the presented 95% CIs. These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

One suggested solution is to re-run on a simpler, i.e. fewer free parameters and then use the output as a starting point for the considered here model. A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

Non-phylogenetic RSS calculations are highly doubtful!  This is probably the result of the optimizer getting stuck at some extreme value, you are advised to rerun the optimization. A possible explanation is that the search procedure finished in a very bad local maximum of the likelihood surface. One suggested solution is to re-run on a simpler, i.e. fewer free parameters and then use the output as a starting point for the considered here model. A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

$testedModels[[70]]$result$FinalFound$ParamSummary$confidence.interval$regression.summary$regression.confidence.interval.comment
[1] "These are confidence intervals for parameters estimated by a GLS conditional on the A and diffusion matrix parameters. In the full covariance matrix of the regression estimators the matrix parameters are entered column wise for the deterministic optimum and row wise for the B matrix. Be careful if some of the parameters were set at fixed values in the user's input, i.e. check if the variances correctly correspond to the presented 95% CIs. These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

$testedModels[[74]]$result$FinalFound$ParamSummary$confidence.interval$regression.summary$regression.confidence.interval.comment
[1] "These are confidence intervals for parameters estimated by a GLS conditional on the A and diffusion matrix parameters. In the full covariance matrix of the regression estimators the matrix parameters are entered column wise for the deterministic optimum and row wise for the B matrix. Be careful if some of the parameters were set at fixed values in the user's input, i.e. check if the variances correctly correspond to the presented 95% CIs. These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

[1] "These are confidence intervals for parameters estimated by a GLS conditional on the A and diffusion matrix parameters. In the full covariance matrix of the regression estimators the matrix parameters are entered column wise for the deterministic optimum and row wise for the B matrix. Be careful if some of the parameters were set at fixed values in the user's input, i.e. check if the variances correctly correspond to the presented 95% CIs. These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

A possible explanation is that the search procedure finished in a very bad local maximum of the likelihood surface. One suggested solution is to re-run on a simpler, i.e. fewer free parameters and then use the output as a starting point for the considered here model. A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

$testedModels[[82]]$result$FinalFound$ParamSummary$confidence.interval$regression.summary$regression.confidence.interval.comment
[1] "These are confidence intervals for parameters estimated by a GLS conditional on the A and diffusion matrix parameters. In the full covariance matrix of the regression estimators the matrix parameters are entered column wise for the deterministic optimum and row wise for the B matrix. Be careful if some of the parameters were set at fixed values in the user's input, i.e. check if the variances correctly correspond to the presented 95% CIs. These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

[1] "These are confidence intervals for parameters estimated by a GLS conditional on the A and diffusion matrix parameters. In the full covariance matrix of the regression estimators the matrix parameters are entered column wise for the deterministic optimum and row wise for the B matrix. Be careful if some of the parameters were set at fixed values in the user's input, i.e. check if the variances correctly correspond to the presented 95% CIs. These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

[1] "WARNING: the covariance matrix for species 23,24,25,27,64,65,66,67,68,69,70,71,72 is not symmetric positive definite! Trying to correct with Matrix::nearPD. Non-phylogenetic RSS calculations are highly doubtful!  This is probably the result of the optimizer getting stuck at some extreme value, you are advised to rerun the optimization. A possible explanation is that the search procedure finished in a very bad local maximum of the likelihood surface. One suggested solution is to re-run on a simpler, i.e. fewer free parameters and then use the output as a starting point for the considered here model. A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

$testedModels[[88]]$result$FinalFound$ParamSummary$confidence.interval$regression.summary$regression.confidence.interval.comment
[1] "These are confidence intervals for parameters estimated by a GLS conditional on the A and diffusion matrix parameters. In the full covariance matrix of the regression estimators the matrix parameters are entered column wise for the deterministic optimum and row wise for the B matrix. These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

Trying to correct with Matrix::nearPD. Non-phylogenetic RSS calculations are highly doubtful!  This is probably the result of the optimizer getting stuck at some extreme value, you are advised to rerun the optimization. A possible explanation is that the search procedure finished in a very bad local maximum of the likelihood surface. One suggested solution is to re-run on a simpler, i.e. fewer free parameters and then use the output as a starting point for the considered here model. A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."

$testedModels[[92]]$result$FinalFound$ParamSummary$confidence.interval$regression.summary$regression.confidence.interval.comment
[1] "These are confidence intervals for parameters estimated by a GLS conditional on the A and diffusion matrix parameters. In the full covariance matrix of the regression estimators the matrix parameters are entered column wise for the deterministic optimum and row wise for the B matrix. Be careful if some of the parameters were set at fixed values in the user's input, i.e. check if the variances correctly correspond to the presented 95% CIs. These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

[1] "These are confidence intervals for parameters estimated by a GLS conditional on the A and diffusion matrix parameters. In the full covariance matrix of the regression estimators the matrix parameters are entered column wise for the deterministic optimum and row wise for the B matrix. Be careful if some of the parameters were set at fixed values in the user's input, i.e. check if the variances correctly correspond to the presented 95% CIs. These are calculated  as estimate =/- (qnorm(0.975), i.e. 0.975 quantile of N(0,1))*(square root of appropriate diagonal element of the covariance matrix), i.e. standard deviation."

A possible explanation is that the search procedure finished in a very bad local maximum of the likelihood surface. One suggested solution is to re-run on a simpler, i.e. fewer free parameters and then use the output as a starting point for the considered here model. A simpler model can be set using the parameters Atype (from experience this is could be the key parameter to focus on) and Syytype. To use the output as a starting point for the optimization, use the start_point_for_optim parameter provided to the estimation function(s). See mvSLOUCH's manual."
